                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">
                        <locus from="3ra" to="105vc"/>
                        <seg type="script">Late nineteenth century–early twentieth century.</seg>
                        <seg type="ink">Black, red.</seg>
                        <desc>Mediocre, relatively large spaces between letters. The hand has slightly different qualities on <locus target="#57vb"/>, where the letters are larger. 
                           It is possible that all three hands in this manuscript represent the same individual at various stages of handwriting development, at different times. 
                           The scribe filled in all supplication formulas only at the beginning of the manuscript; in subsequent supplication formulas, he left blank spaces which were later filled in by <ref target="#h3">Hand 3</ref>.
                        </desc>
                        
                        <seg type="rubrication">Divine names; names of the owners and the scribe; incipits of the commemoration notes; 
                          several groups of lines on the folium opening the commemorative notes for each month; the word <foreign xml:lang="gez">salām</foreign>; elements of the punctuation signs; 
                           elements of Ethiopic numerals; the word <foreign xml:lang="gez">māḫbar</foreign> in the supplication formulas at the end of some commemoration notes; 
                           some of the names of the months in the upper margins of the folia; occasionally, the beginning of the subscriptio: <foreign xml:lang="gez">ተፈጸመ፡</foreign>.
                          </seg>
                     </handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h2" script="Ethiopic">
                        <locus from="106ra" to="217vb"/>
                        <seg type="script">Late nineteenth century–early twentieth century.</seg>
                        <seg type="ink">Black, red.</seg>
                        <desc>Mediocre, very uneven, giving an impression that more than one hand was involved. <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS14757WaldaMikael">Walda Mikāʾel</persName> is mentioned as the scribe in numerous supplication formulas throughout the manuscript, e.g., <locus target="#105rc #114vb #116vb"/>. 
                         He is explicitely mentioned as the scribe on <locus target="#200va"/>. Additionally, his name appears on <locus target="#44rc #99vc #105rc"/>, that is, in the part written by  <ref target="#h1">Hand 1</ref>.
                        This might be a clue that the entire mansucript was indeed written by only one main hand.
                        The scribe filled in all supplication formulas with his name and the name <foreign xml:lang="gez">daqiqa māḫbar</foreign>, referring to the monastic community.</desc>
                        On <locus target="#174r"/> the supplication formulas were left blank. 
                     <list type="abbreviations">
                        <item>
                           <abbr>ሰላ፡</abbr> for <expan>ሰላም፡ </expan> (esp. <locus target="#139vb12"/>) </item>
                        <item>
                           <abbr>ለዓ፡ ዓለ፡</abbr> for <expan>ለዓለመ፡ ዓለም፡ </expan> (e.g., <locus target="#149vb13 #155ra27"/>)</item>
                     </list> 
                        <seg type="rubrication">Divine names; names of the owners and the scribe; incipits of the commemoration notes; 
                           several groups of lines on the folium opening the commemorative notes for each month; the word <foreign xml:lang="gez">salām</foreign>; elements of the punctuation signs; 
                           elements of Ethiopic numerals; the word <foreign xml:lang="gez">māḫbar</foreign> in the supplication formulas at the end of some commemoration notes; 
                           some of the months names in the upper margins of the folia; at the end of the readings for the month, occasionally, the beginning of the subscriptio: <foreign xml:lang="gez">ተፈጸመ፡</foreign>.
                        </seg>
                     </handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h3" script="Ethiopic">
                        <seg type="script">Twentieth century.</seg>
                        <seg type="ink">Black, red (crimson).</seg>
                        <desc>Fine, occasionally careless, with slender letters. It is the hand of <ref target="#e5 #e7"/> and of some of the names written in the supplication formulas in red, such as 
                           <persName role="owner" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS14758TaklaMikael">Takla Mikāʾel</persName>, <persName role="owner" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS14759GabraEgzi">Gabra ʾƎgziʾabǝḥer</persName>, <persName role="owner" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS14771GabraMikael">Gabra Mikāʾel</persName>, <persName role="owner" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS14772NasaraAb">Naṣara ʾAb</persName>, 
                           <persName role="owner" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS14773WaldaMalak">Walda Malʾāk</persName>, <persName role="owner" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS14774GabraMadhen">Gabra Madḫǝn</persName>.
                           The scribe was active during the reign of <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS5226haylase">Ḫāyla Śǝllāse I</persName> whose name appears in many supplication formulas from <locus target="#44rc"/> onwards. </desc>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
